'''Ibrahima Konaté''' ({{IPA|fr|ibʁaimˈa konatˈe}}; born 25 May 1999) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{English football updater|Liverpoo}} club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]]. 

Konaté started off his professional career with [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]], and moved to [[RB Leipzig]] in 2017. After four years with the club, Liverpool signed him in 2021 for a fee of £36&nbsp;million. He won the [[EFL Cup]] and [[FA Cup]] in his first season, and later won the Premier League title with the club in the [[2024–25 Premier League|2024–25 season]].

After representing them at various youth levels, Konaté made his senior debut for France in 2022 and was a member of the team that reached the [[2022 FIFA World Cup final|final]] of the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].

== Early and personal life ==
Ibrahima Konaté<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |title=Squad List: FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022: France (FRA) |publisher=FIFA |page=12 |date=18 December 2022 |access-date=1 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221218195301/https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce44/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |archive-date=18 December 2022 |url-status=live }}</ref> was born on 25 May 1999<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/ibrahima-konat%C3%A9-267477/ |title=Ibrahima Konaté |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |access-date=29 August 2025 |archive-date=29 August 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250829111228/https://www.11v11.com/players/ibrahima-konat%C3%A9-267477/ |url-status=live }}</ref> in Paris.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|title=Ibrahima Konaté|language=fr|newspaper=L'Équipe|location=Paris|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur62329.html|access-date=7 September 2021}}</ref> He grew up in [[Public housing in France|public housing]] in the [[11th arrondissement of Paris]], the second youngest of eight children born to parents from [[Mali]].<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/may/26/ibrahima-konate-liverpool-final-champions-league-final-paris|title=Ibrahima Konaté: 'The final in Paris, my home. I couldn't have dreamed it'|date=26 May 2022|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 May 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Touré|first=Noyine|date=7 February 2019|title=Ibrahima Konaté affole l'Europe|url=https://www.afriquesports.net/football/ibrahima-konate-affole-leurope/}}</ref> His father, Hamady Konaté, died on 21 January 2026.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ibrahima Konate confirms dad's death after missing Liverpool match|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/breaking-ibrahima-konate-confirms-father-33284080|website=Liverpool Echo|date=22 January 2026|access-date=31 January 2026|language=en|first=Mark|last=Jones}}</ref>

He is a fan of [[anime]] and [[manga]], his favourite series being ''[[Attack on Titan]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Northcroft |first=Jonathan |date=27 May 2022 |title=Ibrahima Konaté: I asked Jürgen Klopp, 'If I was your son, what would you advise? |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/ibrahima-konate-i-asked-juergen-klopp-if-i-was-your-son-what-would-you-advise-f6xjg5vxj |access-date=17 April 2022 |newspaper=The Times}}</ref> He is a practising [[Muslims|Muslim]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Muslim football players in French national team reportedly asked to postpone their fasting |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/sports/muslim-football-players-in-french-national-team-reportedly-asked-to-postpone-their-fasting/2860224 |access-date=7 October 2024 |website=aa.com.tr}}</ref>

== Club career ==
=== Early career ===
Konaté played as a teen for [[Paris FC]] youth teams.<ref name="espn_may2021">{{cite news|author1=Julien Laurens|date=28 May 2021|title=Ibrahima Konate's move to Liverpool is just reward for the hard-working French U-21 star|publisher=ESPN|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/english-premier-league/story/4396833/ibrahima-konates-move-to-liverpool-is-just-reward-for-the-hard-working-french-u-21-star}}</ref> When he was 14, he left for [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]] and joined their boarding academy at the age of 15.<ref name="Who is Ibrahima Konate">{{cite news|date=28 May 2021|title=Who is Ibrahima Konate?|publisher=Bundesliga|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/ibrahima-konate-who-is-the-rb-leipzig-france-defender-upamecano-liverpool-10647|access-date=2 June 2021}}</ref> He started his career as a striker before moving to the defence, becoming a centre-back.<ref name="espn_may2021"/>

Konaté made his professional debut for Sochaux in a 1–0 [[Ligue 2]] loss to [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]] on 7 February 2017, at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite web|title=LFP.fr – Ligue de Football Professionnel – Domino's Ligue 2 – Saison 2016/2017 – 24ème journée – FC Sochaux-Montbéliard / AJ Auxerre|url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuille_match/82410|website=lfp.fr}}</ref>

=== RB Leipzig ===
[[File:2019-03-30 Fußball, Männer, 1. Bundesliga, RB Leipzig - Hertha BSC StP 3845 LR10 by Stepro (cropped) 2.jpg|thumb|upright|Konaté playing for [[RB Leipzig]] in 2019]]

After a successful debut season, with 12 games and 1 goal in half a season, Konaté joined [[RB Leipzig]] in the [[Bundesliga]] on 12 June 2017 on a five-year contract by free transfer.<ref>{{cite web|title=RB Leipzig land French talent Ibrahima Konate - bundesliga.com|url=http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/rb-leipzig-sign-french-defender-ibrahima-konate-sochaux-446529.jsp|website=bundesliga.com – the official Bundesliga website|access-date=15 June 2017|archive-date=12 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612182253/http://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/rb-leipzig-sign-french-defender-ibrahima-konate-sochaux-446529.jsp|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RasenBallsport Leipzig – Neuzugang-Ibrahima-Konate|url=http://www.dierotenbullen.com/neuigkeiten/Saison_2016_17/Neuzugang-Ibrahima-Konate.html|website=redbulls}}</ref><ref name="Who is Ibrahima Konate"/> On 27 January 2019, Konaté scored his first Leipzig goal in a 4–0 win against [[Fortuna Düsseldorf]].<ref>{{cite news|date=27 January 2019|title=Fortuna Dusseldorf v RB Leipzig Live Commentary & Result, 27/01/2019, Bundesliga|website=Goal (website)|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/fortuna-d%C3%BCsseldorf-v-rb-leipzig/1ev3ryv0jlqkw2mcivtxtsz8q|access-date=2 June 2021}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
On 28 May 2021, [[Premier League]] side [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] announced that they had reached an agreement with RB Leipzig to acquire Konaté on 1 July, pending international clearance and a work permit being granted to him.<ref name=":2">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/57242659 |date=28 May 2021|title=Liverpool agree deal for Konaté |website=BBC Sport |access-date=28 May 2021}}</ref> The club had already agreed personal terms with the player in April,<ref>{{cite news|title=Liverpool seal £36m deal for RB Leipzig defender Ibrahima Konaté|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/28/liverpool-seal-36m-deal-for-rb-leipzig-defender-ibrahima-konate|access-date=29 May 2021}}</ref> and triggered his release clause of approximately £36&nbsp;million in May 2021.<ref>{{cite news |last=Reddy |first=Melissa |date=28 May 2021 |title=Ibrahima Konate: Liverpool close to sealing transfer after triggering RB Leipzig defender's release clause |newspaper=The Independent |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/liverpool-ibrahima-konate-transfer-leipzig-b1855680.html |access-date=29 May 2021}}</ref>

On 18 September, Konaté made his Liverpool and Premier League debut, starting alongside [[Virgil van Dijk]] and keeping a clean sheet in a 3–0 victory against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Report: Mane, Salah and Keita goals see off Palace at Anfield.|url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/first-team/443819-match-report-crystal-palace-premier-league|access-date=23 September 2021|publisher=Liverpool F.C.}}</ref> He made his second start of the season partnering Virgil van Dijk in the first [[Liverpool F.C.–Manchester United F.C. rivalry|Northwest derby]] of the season, in which Liverpool beat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 5–0. It was the heaviest defeat inflicted on United by Liverpool since 1895 and the heaviest defeat United had suffered without scoring in since 1955.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jackson |first1=Jamie |title=Manchester United's Ole Gunnar Solskjær calls 5–0 thrashing 'darkest day' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/oct/24/manchester-uniteds-ole-gunnar-solskjr-calls-5-0-thrashing-darkest-day |website=The Guardian |date=24 October 2021 |access-date=25 October 2021}}</ref> Konaté won plaudits for how he handled star players like [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Marcus Rashford]], and featured in [[Garth Crooks]]' team of the week, with Crooks saying, "No frills or skills but he does use his power and strength to maximum effect."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Crooks |first1=Garth |title=Garth Crooks' team of the week: Alisson, Keita, Mount, Salah, Foden |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59031790 |access-date=25 October 2021}}</ref>

On 5 April 2022, Konaté scored his first goal for Liverpool, a header in a 3–1 away victory against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|UEFA Champions League]] quarter-final first leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/apr/05/benfica-liverpool-champions-league-quarter-final-first-leg-match-report|title=Luis Díaz returns to Portugal to haunt Benfica and seal Liverpool's first-leg win|last=Hunter|first=Andy|date=5 April 2022|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 April 2022}}</ref> He scored again in the second leg at home on 13 April, which ended in a 3–3 draw with his side winning 6–4 on aggregate to progress to the next round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/apr/13/liverpool-benfica-champions-league-quarter-final-second-leg-match-report|title=Liverpool to face Villarreal in semi-final after thrilling draw with Benfica|last=Hunter|first=Andy|date=13 April 2022|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 February 2026}}</ref> Three days later on 16 April, he scored in a 3–2 [[2021-22 FA Cup|FA Cup]] semi-final win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] at [[Wembley Stadium]], helping Liverpool advance to the [[2022 FA Cup final|final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61120882|title=FA Cup semi-final: Man City 2–3 Liverpool - Sadio Mane double helps Jurgen Klopp's side through
|last=McNulty|first=Phil|date=16 April 2022|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 February 2026}}</ref> Konaté later missed the beginning of the [[2022–23 Liverpool F.C. season|2022–23 season]] through injury.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gorst |first=Paul |date=31 July 2022 |title=Ibrahima Konate injury explained as Keita and Jones absences addressed |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ibrahima-konate-injury-explained-naby-24636392 |access-date=4 November 2022 |website=Liverpool Echo}}</ref>

Having not registered a goal since April 2022, Konaté returned to scoring ways on 17 September 2024 with a header in Liverpool's 3–1 away victory over [[AC Milan]] in the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.givemesport.com/ac-milan-1-3-liverpool-player-ratings-and-match-highlights/|title=AC Milan 1–3 Liverpool: Player Ratings and Match Highlights
|last=Hepburn|first=Daniel|date=17 September 2024|work=GiveMeSport|access-date=1 February 2026}}</ref> On 28 September, he scored his first Premier League goal in a 2–1 away win against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/video/19530/13224131/goal-i-konate-45-2-wolves-0-1-liverpool |title='Moment to cherish!' Ibrahima Konate's first Premier League goal gives Liverpool lead |website=Sky Sports |date=28 September 2024 |access-date=29 September 2024}}</ref>

During the [[2025–26 Liverpool F.C. season|2025–26 season]], Konaté's performances have received criticism from the fans and media.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Arne Slot's woes deepen as awful Liverpool are thrashed by PSV at Anfield|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/nov/26/liverpool-psv-champions-league-match-report|work=The Guardian|date=26 November 2025|access-date=1 December 2025|issn=0261-3077|language=en-GB|first=Andy|last=Hunter}}</ref> On 31 January 2026, after being absent for three games due to the death of his father, Konaté returned to the squad and scored a late goal in a 4–1 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/ibrahima-konate-liverpool-newcastle-united-36649884|title=Liverpool star Ibrahima Konate breaks down in tears after scoring vs Newcastle|website=Daily Mirror|date=31 January 2026|access-date=31 January 2026|last=Reis|first=Bruna}}</ref>

On 20 March 2026, Liverpool released a statement that they are "appalled and disgusted" after racial abuse was targeted towards Konaté on [[social media]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |date=20 March 2026|title=Ibrahima Konate: Liverpool 'disgusted' by racist abuse towards France defender |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/ce8j1j444r3o |access-date=21 March 2026|website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 31 May 2026, Liverpool announced that Konaté would depart the club in the summer following unsuccessful negotiations over a new contract extension.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carroll |first1=James |title=Ibrahima Konate to leave Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/ibrahima-konate-leave-liverpool-fc |website=Liverpool FC |publisher=Liverpool FC |access-date=31 May 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260531160610/https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/ibrahima-konate-leave-liverpool-fc |archive-date=31 May 2026 |date=31 May 2026|url-status=live}}</ref>

== International career ==
[[File:Ibrahima Konaté WC2022.jpg|thumb|upright|Konaté playing for [[France national football team|France]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]

Konaté received his first call-up to the senior [[France national football team|France national team]] on 4 June 2022 for the [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]], replacing [[Raphaël Varane]] due to injury.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Liverpool FC – Ibrahima Konate called up by France |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/ibrahima-konate-called-france |access-date=4 June 2022 |website=liverpoolfc.com |date=4 June 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Husband |first=Ben |date=4 June 2022 |title=Konate handed first France call-up as Varane's suffers more injury woe |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/raphael-varane-injury-ibrahima-konate-27146129 |access-date=4 June 2022 |website=mirror |language=en}}</ref> He made his full international debut on 10 June in a 1–1 draw against [[Austria national football team|Austria]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Austria 1 France 1 |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61766082 |access-date=12 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Ibrahima Konate's season keeps getting better with senior debut for France |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2022/06/ibrahima-konates-season-keeps-getting-better-with-senior-debut-for-france/ |website=This Is Anfield |date=11 June 2022 |access-date=12 June 2022}}</ref> On 9 November, Konaté was included in [[Didier Deschamps]]'s squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], where he helped France reach the [[2022 FIFA World Cup final|final]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sears |first=Jack |date=9 November 2022 |title=Ibrahima Konate named in France squad for World Cup |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2022/11/ibrahima-konate-named-in-france-squad-for-world-cup/ |access-date=10 November 2022 |website=This Is Anfield}}</ref> On 18 November 2024, he captained his country in a 3–1 [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League|UEFA Nations League]] victory against [[Italy national football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=18 November 2024 |title=Didier Deschamps to initiate crunch France captaincy talks with Kylian Mbappé as Ibrahima Konaté's stock grows |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/didier-deschamps-initiate-crunch-france-204000865.html |access-date=20 November 2024 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref>

== Style of play ==
Konaté has been compared to [[Virgil van Dijk]] due to his positional play, tackling, pace and strength.<ref name="Who is Ibrahima Konate"/><ref name=":3">{{cite news|author=Alex Young|date=29 March 2021|title=Who is Ibrahima Konaté: Liverpool target is 'the new Virgil van Dijk' but has worrying injury record|newspaper=Evening Standard|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/who-is-ibrahima-konate-liverpool-fc-transfer-injury-record-stats-style-b926837.html|access-date=2 June 2021}}</ref> Guido Schafer said that: "he is tall, fast, good technique and he is a little bit of Virgil van Dijk. He has very high-class potential. He is a great athlete, he has good speed and there are no silly tackles – he is an intelligent player."<ref name=":3"/> Konaté is also well known for his passing and strength in the air.<ref name=":3"/>

